- Dislikes: glossy, overproduced greatest‑hits/mastering that sounds antiseptic; sprawling experimental/prog doubles with long instrumentals or dense sound‑collage; any compilation that abandons accessible rhythmic guitar arrangements and strong vocal hooks.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those preferences/dislikes
- Mid‑1980s Elton John AOR (candidate 1): Pros relative to my tastes — remastered to restore dynamics and tame late‑’80s sheen; intimate, front‑center vocals; cohesive sequencing that rewards start‑to‑finish listening. Cons — fundamentally piano‑led AOR with tasteful synth textures tucked back and restrained guitars; songwriting and arrangements that are melodic and vocal‑forward but not guitar‑driven or bluesy; overall aesthetic leans toward polished AOR rather than gritty, analog rock. While the remastering and intimate production check some boxes, it lacks the core guitar riffs, driving backbeat and ragged vocal character I prize.
- Rolling‑Stones‑style late‑’70s outtakes (candidate 2): Aligns very closely with core preferences — raw, midrange‑forward bluesy guitar riffs; weathered, forward lead vocals; tight, driving drums (driving backbeat); multi‑tracked harmonies and concise 3–5‑minute riff‑led songs that invite sing‑along; warm analogue sonics, spacious mixes and transient‑preserving mastering that preserve grit and dynamics; a studio‑band live feel and tight LP sequencing that reward front‑to‑back listening. It also avoids the pitfalls I dislike: it’s not overproduced or antiseptic, not sprawling or prog, and it centers accessible rhythmic guitar arrangements and vocal hooks.
3) Choice rationale
- The Rolling‑Stones‑style outtakes (candidate 2) are the clear match for the preferences I listed. The description checks nearly every primary box: bluesy, guitar‑forward riffs and midrange guitar presence, driving drums, weathered lead vocals and multi‑part harmonies that support sing‑along choruses, warm analogue sonics and mastering that preserves transients and grit, and concise, riff‑led tracks with a studio‑band feel — all of which are the qualities I explicitly prioritized.
- The Elton John AOR option, while attractive in its restored dynamics, intimate vocals and strong sequencing, misses the essential element of raw, guitar‑led bluesy rock that I now favor. Its piano‑centric, melodic AOR orientation and restrained guitars place it outside my primary preference set; even a good remaster and cohesive sequencing don’t make it the best fit because it lacks the driving, ragged guitar and analog grit that are decisive for me.
- In short: candidate 2 fulfills the dominant, repeatedly stated criteria (guitar‑forward blues riffs, driving backbeat, ragged vocals, analog warmth, studio cohesion, concise songs), whereas candidate 1 only partially aligns (good sequencing and dynamics) but fails on the central guitar‑forward, gritty rock attributes. Therefore I select the Rolling‑Stones‑style late‑’70s outtakes.

